    {"japanese":"木漏れ日","reading_romaji":"komorebi","translation":"sunlight filtering through tree leaves","what_it_is":"木漏れ日 names something everyone has seen but few languages bother to name outright: the dappled, shifting light that falls through a canopy of leaves. It bundles the sunlight, the leaves, and the shadows into a single word, so instead of describing a scene you just point at it with one breath. It's one of the words most often cited by Japanese speakers as 'impossible to translate' — English needs a whole clause to say what this says in three syllables.","similar_words":[{"japanese":"木陰","romaji":"kokage","translation":"the shade cast by a tree"},{"japanese":"陽だまり","romaji":"hidamari","translation":"a warm, sunny patch (often a cozy spot to sit)"},{"japanese":"そよ風","romaji":"soyokaze","translation":"a gentle, rustling breeze"}],"example_context":"It surfaces on a forest walk in early summer, when you look down and notice the ground is covered in shifting circles of light instead of describing the scene piece by piece.","bonus":"Komorebi shows up constantly in Studio Ghibli-style visual language and is a favorite word among translators precisely because it can't be rendered in one English word — it's frequently listed alongside 'hygge' and 'saudade' in articles about untranslatable feelings.","week_number":1,"day_of_week":"Tuesday","delivered_at":"2026-07-14","source":"routine","is_funword":true},
    {"japanese":"積読","reading_romaji":"tsundoku","translation":"buying books and letting them pile up unread","what_it_is":"積読 fuses 積む (tsumu, to pile up) with 読 (doku, reading), with a sly pun buried inside on 置く (oku, to leave lying around). It names the very specific, slightly guilty habit of buying more books than you'll ever get through, letting them stack up on shelves and nightstands as promises to a future self. Rather than shaming the habit, Japanese gave it a name — which somehow makes it feel like a legitimate hobby instead of a character flaw.","similar_words":[{"japanese":"断捨離","romaji":"danshari","translation":"decluttering — discarding excess to live simpler"},{"japanese":"読書","romaji":"dokusho","translation":"reading (the earnest, guilt-free opposite of tsundoku)"},{"japanese":"もったいない","romaji":"mottainai","translation":"what a waste (the guilt of leaving something precious unused)"}],"example_context":"It surfaces the moment you eye a nightstand stack of five unread books while checking out with a sixth.","bonus":"Tsundoku dates back to satirical wordplay in the 1870s Meiji era, mocking teachers who bought books to look scholarly without ever reading them — today it's been happily reclaimed worldwide by book lovers as the perfect label for their overflowing shelves.","week_number":1,"day_of_week":"Friday","delivered_at":"2026-07-17","source":"routine","is_funword":true}
